Aim
To write a C++ program that demonstrates the use of a pure virtual function and the concept of an abstract class.

Algorithm
Start the program.
Create an abstract base class with a pure virtual function.
Create a derived class that publicly inherits from the base class.
Override the pure virtual function in the derived class.
Create an object of the derived class.
Call the overridden function using the derived class object.
Display the result.
End the program.

Program (C++)
#include <iostream>
using namespace std;
// Abstract class
class Shape {
public:
    virtual void area() = 0;  // pure virtual function
};

// Derived class
class Rectangle : public Shape {
    int length, breadth;

public:
    Rectangle(int l, int b) {
        length = l;
        breadth = b;
    }

    void area() {   // overriding pure virtual function
        cout << "Area of Rectangle = " << (length * breadth) << endl;
    }
};

int main() {
    Shape *ptr;
    Rectangle r(10, 5);

    ptr = &r;
    cout << "Pure Virtual Function Output:" << endl;
    ptr->area();

    return 0;
}

Sample Output (Result)
Pure Virtual Function Output:
Area of Rectangle = 50

Result
The program successfully demonstrates:
Concept of abstract class
Use of pure virtual function
Function overriding in the derived class
Runtime polymorphism using base class pointer
